Silt Type (Nutrient Quality):
  Volcanic/Loess = +50% Food Cap.
  Tropical/Acidic = -30% Food Cap until Upgraded.
  
Flood Predictability (Risk Profile):
  Stable (Nile) = Immune to Drought, No Disaster Risk.
  Unstable (Yellow/Tigris) = 5% chance per turn to trigger a "Washout" event.

Flooding is heavily controlled via infrastructure. Large-scale flood control became globally common during the mid-to-late 19th century and the mid-20th century, driven by industrial-era engineering, steam power, and reinforced concrete.

Historically, early civilizations used local infrastructure (dykes and levees), but they could not control the river itself; they could only protect small pockets of land. True, comprehensive river control emerged in two distinct historical waves.

Wave 1: The Industrial Era Channelization (Mid-to-Late 1800s)

Wave 2: The Age of Mega-Dams (Mid-1900s)

Controlling flooding reduces fertility without extensive irrigation 

Irrigation extends river bonus.

In agricultural physics, this limit is governed by evaporative water loss.




